leave Eastern
Aleppo.

13:57.003 --> 14:03.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many of the evacuees were taken
first to the
rebel-held town of al-Rashideen,
west of Aleppo.

14:03.843 --> 14:09.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They received much-needed food,
water and
humanitarian aid, and, by
nightfall, they

14:09.949 --> 14:14.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
huddled around fires to stay
warm, and recounted
the horror they left behind.

14:14.954 --> 14:19.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAHMOUD ABU MOHAMMAD, Evacuee
(through translator):
We left Aleppo to escape the
relentless shelling.

14:19.726 --> 14:21.260 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
All the houses were damaged.

14:21.294 --> 14:24.297 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Not a single one remained
undamaged.

14:24.330 --> 14:26.265 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We left because of the heavy
airstrikes.

14:26.299 --> 14:32.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Late in the day,
Turkish officials
estimated some 20,000 people had
been bussed

14:32.772 --> 14:36.008 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
out of Eastern Aleppo so far.

14:36.042 --> 14:41.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on what comes next for
Aleppo's evacuated
civilians and what U.N. monitors
will be able

14:41.748 --> 14:46.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to do, I'm joined by former
British Foreign
Secretary David Miliband.

14:46.786 --> 14:49.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He's now CEO of the
International Rescue Committee.

14:49.856 --> 14:51.824 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
David Miliband, welcome.

14:51.858 --> 14:55.995 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I think it's pretty
self-evident, but why
are these monitors necessary?

14:56.028 --> 15:00.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND, Former British
Foreign Secretary:
The simple reason for these
monitors is that

15:00.967 --> 15:06.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Aleppo has not just been a site
of terrible
death and destruction over the
last few months.

15:06.806 --> 15:13.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's also been the site of the
destruction
of basic norms of international
humanitarian

15:13.079 --> 15:19.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
law, not just the besiegement or
the randomized
bombings of civilian centers,
including a

15:19.051 --> 15:24.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hospital supported by the
International Rescue
Committee, but also
door-to-door, cold-blooded

15:24.524 --> 15:28.828 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
murder by militias working their
way through
the city.

15:28.861 --> 15:32.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think it's very important
that there
are people on the ground who
can, by bearing

15:32.565 --> 15:36.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
witness or threatening to bear
witness to
what's happening, try to put a
stop to it.

15:36.869 --> 15:39.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Everything that we're seeing and
hearing from
people who have fled the city is
that the

15:39.906 --> 15:42.175 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fear levels are at terrifying
levels.

15:42.208 --> 15:45.711 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But can they put
a stop to
it by monitoring?

15:45.745 --> 15:50.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: I think that the
monitoring
on its own is only part of the
answer.

15:50.850 --> 15:56.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obviously, there's got to be a
decision from
the Syrian government, and their
Russian backers,

15:56.088 --> 16:00.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the Hezbollah militias that
have been
working their way through the
city, about

16:00.726 --> 16:02.361 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what they're going to do next.

16:02.395 --> 16:07.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obviously, the Russians voted
for this resolution
in the Security Council today.

16:07.266 --> 16:09.702 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Some people were surprised by
that.

16:09.735 --> 16:15.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if it does mean a halt to
the terrible
scenes that we have seen over
the last week

16:15.842 --> 16:18.444 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
inside Aleppo, that's obviously
a step forward.

16:18.477 --> 16:24.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The people that we're meeting 20
kilometers
to the west of Aleppo in the
governorate of

16:24.383 --> 16:29.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Idlib are concerned that they're
moving from
one killing zone into another,
because obviously

16:29.355 --> 16:35.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the great fear is that the
tactics that have
been used in Aleppo are now
deployed in Idlib,

16:35.428 --> 16:38.698 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which is 1.9 million people
across the whole
governorate.

16:38.731 --> 16:43.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The bombing, the murder, the
great danger
is that that flows with the
people to the

16:43.169 --> 16:45.004 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
west.

16:45.037 --> 16:48.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And I want to ask
you about
that, but when it comes to
Aleppo, is it believed,

16:48.507 --> 16:54.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is it understood that these
monitors are going
to be in a position to stop
whatever indiscriminate

16:54.714 --> 16:58.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
killing or other terrible things
are happening
to these people as they leave?

16:58.918 --> 17:02.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, at best,
they can bear
witness to it.

17:02.121 --> 17:05.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're obviously not in a
position to intervene
militarily.

17:05.391 --> 17:09.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not a U.N. peacekeeping
force that has
been deployed as a result of
this resolution

17:09.996 --> 17:11.764 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
today.

17:11.797 --> 17:17.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a group of monitors who are
unarmed and
who are there to monitor the
conduct of the

17:17.937 --> 17:20.640 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
security and other forces and
report on it.

17:20.673 --> 17:26.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, it is right and better for
there to be
some degree of international
presence, but,

17:26.746 --> 17:32.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
obviously, that is cold comfort
to very, very
scared residents of Aleppo who
have been the

17:32.485 --> 17:36.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
subject of this brutal assault
not just over
the last few weeks, but over the
last few

17:36.989 --> 17:38.824 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
years.

17:38.858 --> 17:41.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, to the
point you were
making a moment ago, David
Miliband, the place

17:41.060 --> 17:46.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where these evacuees are going,
Idlib province,
as we reported, is expected to
be the next

17:46.632 --> 17:49.802 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
front in the government's focus.

17:49.835 --> 17:52.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why are they any safer there
than they were
in Aleppo?

17:52.939 --> 17:57.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, I think
that the words
of the people who are fleeing
tell it all.

17:57.243 --> 18:00.012 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They say, we had to get out of
hell.

18:00.046 --> 18:04.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they don't know where --
whether the place
they're going to is going to be
any better,

18:04.083 --> 18:06.018 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but there is a chance that it
might.

18:06.052 --> 18:12.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Idlib has a different
composition, population
composition, and a different
group of rebel

18:12.058 --> 18:14.660 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
fighters who are dominant there.

18:14.694 --> 18:19.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's an area that combines a
large government
with Idlib City, which is a
confined urban

18:19.999 --> 18:21.801 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
area like Aleppo.

18:21.834 --> 18:27.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's going to be a much tougher
military effort,
I think, on the part of the
Syrian and the

18:27.273 --> 18:29.041 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Russian forces.

18:29.075 --> 18:32.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the great plea -- and I'm
afraid it is
only a plea from the
international community

18:32.278 --> 18:38.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the moment -- is that the
tactics of bombardment,
besiegement and then
door-to-door murder are

18:38.184 --> 18:39.952 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
not deployed in Idlib.

18:39.986 --> 18:46.592 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And in the absence of
international military
support, then it can only be a
diplomatic

18:46.625 --> 18:52.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
plea that the way this war takes
its next
turn is going to be critical for
whether any

18:52.631 --> 18:55.968 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
stability comes back to Syria in
the future.

18:56.002 --> 18:59.372 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You reported yourselves that
ISIS have been
resurgent in taking Palmyra.

18:59.405 --> 19:01.207 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

19:01.240 --> 19:05.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: And we know from
history that
the way wars are concluded is
absolutely the

19:05.411 --> 19:07.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
key to whether or not there is
any peace to
be kept.

19:07.580 --> 19:13.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, I guess my
question is,
is there an expectation that
what these monitors

19:13.219 --> 19:17.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are doing in Aleppo could --
they could just
be moved next to Idlib to
prevent the same

19:17.990 --> 19:23.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
kind of thing from happening
there and then
onto the next place where the
government is

19:23.763 --> 19:25.464 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
moving in?

19:25.498 --> 19:29.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, the
terrible truth of
the last few weeks is that there
has been

19:29.402 --> 19:34.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
plenty on social media and
elsewhere explaining
what's been going on in Aleppo,
but it's not

19:34.740 --> 19:40.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been possible to rally any kind
of sufficient
diplomatic, political or other
pressure on

19:40.579 --> 19:46.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
those taking part in these
activities to prevent
the kind of horrific scenes that
you broadcast

19:46.085 --> 19:48.287 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
last week and that are feared in
the future.

19:48.320 --> 19:54.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is now a real test of
whether or not
the Russians and their Iranian
backers are

19:54.460 --> 19:59.698 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
serious about winning a
sustainable peace
in Syria, whether they are
serious about taking

19:59.732 --> 20:05.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on some of the rebel elements
who are affiliated
with al-Qaida, or whether this
is simply a

20:05.671 --> 20:12.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pretense and a fig leaf for a
wider attempt
to drive large sections of the
Syrian population

20:12.344 --> 20:16.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out of their homes as part of a
bloody attempt
to restore order.

20:16.248 --> 20:20.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally, do you
believe they
are serious, based on what you
know?

20:20.619 --> 20:25.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, I have had
-- over the
last five years of this
conflict, the International

20:25.624 --> 20:31.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Rescue Committee has had between
1,200 and
2,500 local staff on the ground
through this.

20:31.997 --> 20:37.069 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And it has been the most
appalling descent
into hell for all of the people
who work for

20:37.103 --> 20:38.838 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
us.

20:38.871 --> 20:42.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All of the norms under which
international
humanitarian organizations work
have been

20:42.341 --> 20:43.742 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
violated.

20:43.776 --> 20:47.012 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Never did I think we would see
the day of
U.N. convoys being bombed.

20:47.046 --> 20:52.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And never did I think we would
go back to
the days when there seemed to be
no accountability

20:52.451 --> 20:55.287 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for the most grotesque abuses of
human rights.

20:55.321 --> 20:58.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I cannot -- of even human
life, never
mind human rights.

20:58.858 --> 21:02.695 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, for me to sit here
comfortably and tell
you I'm confident about the
future would be

21:02.728 --> 21:03.696 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
quite wrong.

21:03.729 --> 21:05.764 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is a desperate situation in
Syria.

21:05.798 --> 21:07.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have got my own staff in the
front line.

21:07.967 --> 21:13.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we're desperate for the kind
of coordinated
and impactful political and
diplomatic pressure

21:13.038 --> 21:16.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that can ease some of the plight
of the civilians
and allow us to get on with our
work.

21:16.942 --> 21:20.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David Miliband,
the CEO of
the International Rescue
Committee, we thank

21:20.913 --> 21:21.881 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you.

21:21.914 --> 21:26.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Thank you very
much.

21:26.886 --> 21:39.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Back in this
country, president-elect
Donald Trump is now one step
closer to officially

21:39.398 --> 21:41.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
sealing his victory.

21:41.267 --> 21:46.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the debate over the value of
the Electoral
College has intensified this
year, in part

21:46.505 --> 21:51.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
